# Content Production Batch Standards

## Weekly Content Volume (Non-Negotiable)

Every week in a production batch must contain exactly **10 core pieces**, plus 2-5 derivative clips:

| Channel | Pieces per Week | Format |
|---------|----------------|--------|
| Anchor blog post | 1 | Long-form article, signs off "Capably Yours, Jared" |
| Video podcast script | 1 | Solo episode (max 25 min), recorded as video podcast, uploaded to YouTube + podcast platforms |
| Short-form clips | 2-5 (from podcast) | Extracted from podcast; vertical video for YouTube Shorts + Instagram Reels |
| LinkedIn text posts | 3 | Professional insight posts, no sign-off; see `rules/linkedin-content-creation-guidelines.md` |
| Facebook posts | 5 | Warmer/personal tone, no sign-off |

**LinkedIn (Capable Wealth):** Hooks, length (180–230 words), cadence (Tue–Wed–Thu), hashtags, loss framing, and quality gates are defined in [rules/linkedin-content-creation-guidelines.md](../../rules/linkedin-content-creation-guidelines.md). Each LinkedIn draft must pass Section 6 of that document before approval.

**LinkedIn native video (recommended):** One ~60s native upload per week from podcast/YouTube material (separate distribution lane). Optional carousel outline for mechanism-style posts. See the same guidelines, Rule 12.

Clips are derivative content, not net-new creation. They are identified during script writing via the Clip Extraction Map and produced from the recorded podcast episode. The clip count varies organically: only extract where a segment naturally stands alone. Do not force clips to hit a number.

## File Naming Convention

```
week-N-blog-slug.md
week-N-podcast-slug.md
week-N-clip-1.md through week-N-clip-5.md
week-N-linkedin-1.md through week-N-linkedin-3.md
week-N-linkedin-native-video.md (optional but recommended; Rule 12)
week-N-facebook-1.md through week-N-facebook-5.md
```

Clip files are created after the podcast script is finalized. Each clip file contains the trimmed script, caption text, platform tags, and a cover frame visual asset brief. The podcast draft file contains the Clip Extraction Map (planning stage); the individual clip files are the production-ready output.

## File Template (All Content Types)

1. **Title** (H1)
2. **Post Metadata** -- Type, Week, Theme, Quarterly plan reference, Strategic context, **Story classifications used**
3. **Visual Assets** -- Image type, Rationale, AI image prompt (9-point standard, Capable Wealth palette only), Text overlay, Platform/dimensions
4. **Clip Extraction Map** (video podcast scripts only) -- 2-5 clip candidates with source segment, hook line, core insight, platform tags, estimated duration
5. **Full content draft** -- Jared's voice per voice-profile.md and content-recipe.md, all stories/examples classified per content-integrity rule. No formulaic "Not X, but Y" / "Not because X, because Y" pivots (see brand_config.json `language_to_avoid`); state the cause directly.
6. **Quality Checklist** -- Voice Alignment, Audience Specificity, Relevance Validation, Pull Signal Design, Visual Assets, **Content Integrity**, **Short-Form Clips** (podcast only), **LinkedIn guidelines** (LinkedIn text posts only: Section 6 of `rules/linkedin-content-creation-guidelines.md`)

**LinkedIn post metadata:** Include **Planned publish day:** Tuesday, Wednesday, or Thursday (see below). Batch weeks still start Monday for planning; LinkedIn text posts publish mid-week only.

## LinkedIn text post roles and schedule

| File | Planned publish day | Role |
|------|----------------------|------|
| `week-N-linkedin-1.md` | Tuesday | Hook post: strongest number, trust gap, scroll-stop |
| `week-N-linkedin-2.md` | Wednesday | Story post: specific surgeon scenario |
| `week-N-linkedin-3.md` | Thursday | Mechanism post: one tactical "how it works" angle |

## Image Type Variety (Non-Negotiable)

**Facebook:** Each week's **5** Facebook posts must use a mix of visual styles. A feed of identical text-on-block cards is not acceptable.

| Post # | Required Image Type (Facebook) |
|--------|-------------------------------|
| 1 of 5 | Stat highlight card OR quote card (text-on-block) |
| 2 of 5 | Conceptual photograph (photorealistic people or environment) |
| 3 of 5 | Simple infographic or data visualization |
| 4 of 5 | Conceptual photograph (photorealistic, different subject from #2) |
| 5 of 5 | Any type not already used this week |

**LinkedIn (3 text posts per week):** Use three distinct visual types. Recommended mapping:

| Post # | Required Image Type (LinkedIn) |
|--------|-------------------------------|
| 1 of 3 (Tuesday hook) | Stat highlight card OR quote card (max one text-on-block per week on LinkedIn) |
| 2 of 3 (Wednesday story) | Conceptual photograph (photorealistic) |
| 3 of 3 (Thursday mechanism) | Simple infographic or data visualization |

Hard rules:

- Max 1 text-on-block card per **5** Facebook posts per week; max **1** text-on-block among the **3** LinkedIn posts per week
- Conceptual photographs must be photorealistic (AI-generated photography), never cartoon or illustrated
- People in images: professional, mid-to-late career, natural lighting, calm expressions, medical-adjacent or professional environments
- Each week's images must look visually distinct when viewed as a set in a feed
- Blog heroes default to conceptual photograph; podcast/YouTube thumbnails use conceptual photograph or scene-based imagery

See content-recipe.md Section 10 "Weekly Image Type Distribution" for full guidance and example prompts (Examples D and E).

## Image Prompt Variation (Non-Negotiable)

The Image Type Variety rules above ensure the correct *category* rotation (stat card, photo, infographic). This section ensures visual *uniqueness within each category* so that images across a week and across a batch look distinct when viewed as a set in a feed.

### Text-on-block cards (stat highlights and quote cards)

No two text-on-block cards in the same batch may share the same background color. Rotate through the palette:

| Card # in batch | Background | Primary text color | Accent |
|-----------------|------------|-------------------|--------|
| 1st | Deep Muted Blue (#243A4B) | Antique Gold / Off-White | Antique Gold accent line |
| 2nd | Charcoal (#1E2428) | Off-White | Antique Gold accent line |
| 3rd | Off-White (#F6F7F5) | Charcoal / Deep Muted Blue | Antique Gold accent line |
| 4th+ | Repeat cycle, but vary layout (see below) | | |

Layout variation is equally important. Not every card should be centered-text-with-horizontal-accent-line. Alternate among these compositions across the batch:

- **Centered stack:** Primary number/quote centered, subtitle below, accent line below (the default; use for at most half of text-on-block cards in a batch)
- **Asymmetric anchor:** Primary number large and left-aligned in the upper-left quadrant, supporting text right-aligned or bottom-right, no accent line
- **Split comparison:** Two numbers side by side (e.g., strikethrough vs. corrected), vertical divider between them
- **Full-bleed number:** Single oversized number filling 60%+ of the canvas, minimal supporting text below in small type
- **Stacked contrast:** Two short lines of text stacked with a color shift between them (e.g., line 1 in Off-White, line 2 in Antique Gold), no accent line

### Conceptual photographs

Each week's conceptual photographs must depict **different subjects, settings, and compositions**. Within a single batch, no two conceptual photographs may describe the same core scene.

**Subject/setting rotation (max 1 per week across all platforms combined):**

| Setting category | Example scenes |
|-----------------|---------------|
| Office/desk | Professional reviewing documents, desk still-life with pen and glasses |
| Corridor/path/road | Hospital corridor, walking path, open road |
| Outdoor/landscape | Coastline at golden hour, campus courtyard, park bench |
| People in conversation | Two professionals at a conference table, advisor and client |
| Object/still-life close-up | Surgical instrument on clean surface, brass desk clock, leather planner |
| Domestic/non-work | Kitchen morning scene, home study, lakeside dock |
| Architectural/exterior | Medical office building at golden hour, modern campus entrance |

**Cross-week uniqueness:** When generating multiple weeks in a single batch, maintain a running awareness of subjects already used. No conceptual photograph subject may repeat in back-to-back weeks. If Week N uses "professional at desk" and "corridor," Week N+1 must use different settings (e.g., "outdoor landscape" and "object close-up").

**Person descriptions must vary:** Do not reuse the same person archetype (e.g., "early-60s silver-haired man") in more than 2 conceptual photos per batch. Vary age (late 40s through mid-60s), gender, and presentation across the batch. When a photo includes no people, state that explicitly rather than defaulting to the recurring archetype.

### Infographics

Vary the layout structure across the batch. Not every infographic should be a two-column comparison. Rotate among:

- **Timeline** (horizontal or vertical, with milestone markers)
- **Checklist** (checkbox rows with labels)
- **Comparison columns** (side-by-side with divider)
- **Step flow** (numbered sequential steps with arrows or connectors)
- **Single-stat callout** (one large number with supporting bullet points below)
- **Before/after** (stacked horizontal bars or gauges)

No two infographics in the same week may use the same layout structure.

### Clip cover frames

Clip cover frames are the most templated asset. To prevent visual monotony across 2-5 clips per week:

- **Vary the background color** across clips within the same week. Use Deep Muted Blue for at most 2 clips; use Charcoal or Off-White (inverted text) for the others.
- **Vary the text hierarchy.** Not every cover should be "big number top, subtitle middle, subtext bottom." Alternatives: question-as-headline (no number), side-by-side comparison layout, list format (numbered items), quote-style (large italic text).
- **Vary the accent element.** Not every cover needs a horizontal accent line at 40% width. Alternatives: vertical accent bar on the left edge, no accent element (let whitespace separate sections), a thin border frame, or a subtle background color block behind the primary text.

### Cross-platform deduplication

When the same data point or visual concept appears on multiple platforms in the same week (e.g., a $330K stat on Facebook, LinkedIn, and a clip cover), each platform's image must use a **different visual treatment:**

- One platform gets the stat highlight card
- Another gets the number embedded in an infographic or comparison layout
- The clip cover uses a different background color and layout from both

Never produce the same visual concept with only a dimension change (e.g., 1200x630 vs. 1080x1080 vs. 1080x1920 of the same centered-number-on-blue card).

## Video Podcast Script Structure

Recorded as a video podcast and uploaded to YouTube. Audio is also distributed to podcast platforms (Apple Podcasts, Spotify). Audio must stand alone; the video version is a different consumption angle of the same content.

Structure:

- **COLD OPEN** (30-60s) -- Hook that pulls the listener in immediately
- **INTRO AND CONTEXT** (1-2 min) -- Set the stakes, why this matters now
- **MAIN SEGMENTS** (3-5 segments, each 3-5 min) -- Core teaching, math examples, frameworks. Annotate with `[CLIP-CANDIDATE]` where a moment could stand alone as a short-form clip.
- **LISTENER TAKEAWAY** (1-2 min) -- Actionable summary, one thing to do this week
- **PHILOSOPHICAL CLOSE** (1-2 min) -- Connect to bigger life principles

Tone: Conversational, exploratory, Jared thinking out loud with the listener. More depth and nuance than blog.

Visual asset: Podcast cover art card (1400x1400 for podcast feeds, 1280x720 variant for YouTube thumbnail).

## Clip Extraction (from Video Podcast)

Every video podcast script includes a Clip Extraction Map identifying 2-5 segments that can be extracted as standalone short-form clips for YouTube Shorts and Instagram Reels.

Clip identification rules:

- Minimum 2 clips per episode, maximum 5
- Only extract where a segment naturally stands alone (no forced clips)
- Each clip must make sense without any context from the rest of the episode
- Each clip must have a clear hook in the first 3 seconds
- Each clip must end with a clean takeaway or curiosity beat, never mid-sentence
- Tag each clip: `[YT-SHORT]`, `[IG-REEL]`, or `[BOTH]`

What to look for when marking `[CLIP-CANDIDATE]` during script writing:

- A striking math reveal or data point that shocks on its own
- A contrarian take or myth-bust that needs no setup
- A self-contained explanation or framework
- A vivid metaphor or analogy that lands immediately
- A direct, actionable recommendation

Platform-specific guidance:

| Platform | Target Duration | Format | Pacing |
|----------|----------------|--------|--------|
| YouTube Shorts | 45-58 seconds | 9:16 vertical, 1080x1920px | Punchier, faster; end with curiosity driver to full episode |
| Instagram Reels | 60-90 seconds | 9:16 vertical, 1080x1920px | Slightly more breathing room; can include text overlays |

Both platforms: captions required (most viewers watch muted), keep critical content within center 4:5 safe zone (platform UI overlays top/bottom 10%).

## Social Post Expansion

**LinkedIn:** Do not add a fourth or fifth text post to "fill" the week. Extra angles go into **native LinkedIn video**, **carousel (PDF) outline**, short-form clips, Facebook, or the blog. When the quarterly plan lists extra LinkedIn hooks, merge the best into three posts or reassign to those formats.

**Facebook:** When the quarterly plan briefs fewer than 5 Facebook posts, create additional posts by:
- Isolating individual talking points from the anchor/podcast as standalone insights
- Creating story-driven variations
- Adding reflective questions (not hard CTAs)
- Building week-to-week narrative continuity

## Opening Line Variation (Non-Negotiable)

Content openings across a week and across a batch must feel fresh. A reader scrolling a feed must not encounter the same rhetorical pattern twice in the same week on the same platform, or three times in a batch.

### Banned patterns (never use within a single batch)

The following exact phrase templates are overused and must not appear more than **once per batch** across all platforms combined:

- "Most [professionals] don't [verb] because [reason]..." (the "Most X don't Y" template)
- "Here's what nobody tells you about..." / "Here's what most [X] miss..."
- "The math is simple:" / "The math is straightforward:"
- Any opening that leads with "I talk to [surgeons/specialists/professionals] every [week/day]..."

If a phrase template appears once in a batch, flag it in the quality checklist so it is not reused in subsequent files within the same batch.

### Within-week rules (same platform)

No two posts on the **same platform in the same week** may open with the same rhetorical device. Rhetorical device categories:

| Device | Example | Max per week per platform |
|--------|---------|--------------------------|
| **Provocative stat** | "$330,000. That's the average..." | 1 |
| **Direct question** | "When was the last time you...?" | 1 |
| **Scenario/scene** | "Picture this: You're sitting in..." | 1 |
| **Contrarian assertion** | "The highest-earning surgeons rarely..." | 1 |
| **Anecdote lead** | "A few months ago, a specialist called me..." | 1 |
| **Simple declarative** | "Practice transitions take 18 months." | 1 |
| **If/when conditional** | "If you're five years from retirement..." | 1 |

With 5 Facebook posts per week, use at least 4 different devices from the table. With 3 LinkedIn posts per week, use 3 different devices.

### Cross-week rules (within a batch)

When generating multiple weeks in a batch, maintain a running log of which devices have been used for the first post slot on each platform. The first Facebook post and first LinkedIn post in consecutive weeks must use **different** opening devices.

### Sentence structure variation

Beyond rhetorical device, vary the syntactic structure of opening sentences:

- Not every opening should be a short punchy fragment. Alternate between:
  - Short declarative (under 10 words)
  - Mid-length compound sentence (15-25 words)
  - Question
  - Conditional clause leading to a punchline
- Avoid opening 3+ posts in the same week with sentences under 8 words. At least 2 posts per week should open with sentences of 15+ words.

### Blog and podcast openings

Blog posts and podcast cold opens have more latitude but still must not repeat the same pattern within a batch:

- No two blogs in the same batch may open with the same device (stat, question, scenario, etc.)
- No two podcast cold opens in the same batch may use the same hook structure (e.g., both opening with "What if I told you...")

## Excel Summary Sync (Non-Negotiable)

Whenever any content draft in a batch folder is created, modified, or deleted, the Excel summary must be regenerated immediately:

```
python3 src/export_content_batch.py outputs/drafts/content-batch-[YYYY-MM-DD]/
```

This produces `content-batch-summary-[YYYYMMDD].xlsx` in the same folder. The spreadsheet is the primary handoff artifact and must always reflect the current state of the markdown drafts. Never leave the xlsx out of sync.

## Content Integrity (Non-Negotiable)

Before drafting any content, read `brand/experience-inventory.md`. All client stories, experience claims, and case studies must comply with the content integrity rule (`.cursor/rules/content-integrity.mdc`) and content-recipe.md Section 5.1.

Key requirements:

- Every client story must be classified as `[REAL-ANONYMIZED]`, `[ILLUSTRATIVE]`, or `[GENERAL-PRINCIPLE]`
- Classifications must be listed in Post Metadata under "Story classifications used"
- Illustrative examples must use approved framing language; never imply a real client interaction that isn't sourced from the experience inventory
- The Content Integrity checklist (see content-recipe.md Section 13) must appear in every draft's Quality Checklist and all items must pass
- If the experience inventory is unpopulated, all stories default to `[ILLUSTRATIVE]` with appropriate framing

